<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910103-0024</DOCNO><DOCID>910103-0024.</DOCID><HL>   Abreast of the Market:   Industrials Drop 23.02 as Investors   React to Deeper Recessionary Signs   ----   By Craig Torres and Craig S. Smith   Staff Reporters of The Wall Street Journal</HL><DATE>01/03/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C2</SO><IN>STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)U.S. STOCK MARKET STATISTICS (STT)STOCK INDEXES (NDX)NYSE GENERAL MARKET COMMENTARY (NYS)</IN><LP>   NEW YORK -- Signs of further economic deterioration lastmonth knocked stock prices sharply lower on the first day of1991 trading.   The Dow Jones Industrial Average lost 23.02 points to2610.64, the steepest decline since Nov. 20, 1990, when itfell 35.15.</LP><TEXT>   Asset allocators moved into stocks in early trading,keeping the market near unchanged levels even though therewas little interest seen from other large investors. Assetallocators shift between stocks, bonds and cash, and often goagainst the trend of other investors.   But in late trading, after the asset allocators hadfinished buying, big speculators moved out of stocks intobonds, knocking the market lower, traders said.   Trading activity continued in holiday sluggishness, with126,280,000 shares changing hands on the New York StockExchange. Declining issues on the Big Board outnumberedadvancers, 852 to 725.   Stocks fell swiftly yesterday because buyers thinkeconomic and political risks appear too great now. &quot;The majorthing people are trying to grapple with is how deep and howlong&quot; the economic decline will be, said David Rajala, adirector at One Federal Asset Management. &quot;This cycle feelsdifferent than previous economic cycles.&quot;   Treasury bonds rallied sharply yesterday amid furthersigns of economic weakness. An index of economic activitypublished by the nation's purchasing managers fell to 40.4%in December, the lowest level since the last prior recessionin 1982.   Commodity prices also fell sharply yesterday. An indexpublished by the Commodity Research Bureau, a division ofKnight-Ridder Inc., fell 4.18 points to 218.46, the lowestlevel since last May.   &quot;I am looking at deflation and I'm scared,&quot; said StuartShinbein, senior technical analyst at the bureau.   But some money managers continue to venture into stockssensitive to the economic cycle, despite tumbling commodityprices and bad economic news. Yesterday, nonferrous metals,trucking, heavy machinery and home construction stock groupsshowed gains.   Aluminum Co. of America added 3/8 to 58, Deere rose 5/8 to47 1/2 and Phelps Dodge was up 1/4 to 56 7/8.   Profit-taking depressed many of the last year's &quot;safehaven&quot; growth issues. Among them, Procter andamp; Gamble dropped 11/8 to 85 1/2; Philip Morris sank 7/8 to 50 7/8; Merck eased3/8 to 89 1/2 and Coca-Cola Co. fell 1 1/4 to 45 1/4.   Meanwhile, Standard andamp; Poor's Corp. said only 1,263dividend increases were reported last year by some 7,000companies monitored by the firm. That was 24% below 1989, andthe fewest increases since 1962, excepting 1970 and 1971 whenfederal anti-inflation laws restrained dividend activity.   Dividend cuts totaled 143, while 266 omissions werereported, the highest amount of negative dividend activitysince 1982, Sandamp;P said.   Arnold Kaufman, editor of Sandamp;P's &quot;Outlook&quot; newsletter, saidmany large companies, such as food, drug and householdproducts concerns, have above-average earnings and areincreasing dividends. However, Sandamp;P expects 5% dividend growthfrom companies in its index this year, below the average of8.6% over the past 15 years.   More than eight million shares of Manufacturers Hanoverchanged hands in an apparent dividend play. Manufacturerspays an 82-cent dividend to shares of record yesterday. Thestock gained 1/8 to 21 1/4.   Other big bank stocks were higher, even as many cut theirprime lending rates. Chemical Banking rose 1/2 to 11 1/4 andBankers Trust gained 1/4 to 43 5/8.   Student Loan Marketing Association gained 1 1/2 to 47 3/4.Sallie Mae said it agreed to purchase all of ChaseManhattan's $1.2 billion in insured student loans over thenext seven months and all additional such loans originated byChase over the next five years. Chase added 1/8 to 10 5/8.   Paramount Communications advanced 1 1/2 to 42 3/8. Theentertainment conglomerate denied reports out of Japan thatit is seeking to sell its film-producing unit.   Northrop rose 5/8 to 18. The Air Force said it intends togo ahead with plans to build all 75 B-2 Stealth bombersapproved by Defense Secretary Richard B. Cheney, according toa report in the Washington Post. Northrop's stock fell 1 7/8on Monday on a report about freezing production at thecurrent level of 15 planes. Northrop is the prime contractoron the plane.   Pinelands, the television station spinoff from MCA thatbegan when-issued trading Monday, jumped 1 7/8 to 19 5/8 onvolume of nearly one million shares. This newspaper reportedthat the heavy volume in the stock on Monday, when about 1.5million shares changed hands, reflects a belief among tradersthat Pinelands will be sold. The company's chairman, LawrenceP. Fraiburg, said Pinelands' current management wants to runthe station independently, however.   Acuson fell 1 1/2 to 25 3/4. The company's chairman andpresident have sold some of their shares in the ultrasoundimaging equipment maker, this newspaper reported. Acuson lastweek said it was ordered to pay a $6.3 million award pluslegal fees and costs as the result of an arbitratedsettlement over a marketing dispute with Advanced TechnologyLaboratories, a unit of Westmark International.   Abbott Laboratories dropped 1 3/4 to 43 1/4 afterDonaldson, Lufkin andamp; Jenrette cut its rating on the companyand removed the company's stock from the firm's recommendedlist.   Johnson andamp; Johnson eased 1 3/4 to 70 in active trading.Jandamp;J's Ortho Pharmaceutical unit said it was approved by theFood and Drug Administration to distribute Amgen's Procritfor the treatment of anemia in AZT-treated HIV-infectedpatients.   TRW fell 1 5/8 to 36 1/4. The company said it will post&quot;disappointing&quot; fourth-quarter earnings because of weaknessin its major markets and continued development costs for itsauto air bags, Chairman Joseph T. Gorman said.   Rupert Murdoch's News Corp. said its bankers mightcomplete a multibillion-dollar debt restructuring agreementnext week. News Corp. added 1/4 to 8 1/8.   General Dynamics rose 1/8 to 25 3/8, while McDonnellDouglas dropped 1 1/4 to 37 5/8. The two defense contractorsare expected to submit a proposal seeking relief from costoverruns in developing the A-12 attack plane for the Navy.   Toys &quot;R&quot; Us added 5/8 to 23 1/8. Its sales for theeight-week Christmas selling season ended Dec. 24 were up 7%from a year ago, although sales in stores open a yeardeclined 6% during the Christmas season compared with a yearago.   Kaufman andamp; Broad Home gained 3/4 to 10. The home buildersaid it increased its unsecured domestic revolving creditfacility to $265 million from $200 million. The maturity dateof the facility has been extended to October 1993.   Ralston was off 4 3/8 to 98 1/8. Goldman Sachs is said tohave lowered its investment rating on the stock, according toDow Jones Professional Investor Report.   Jamesway rose 1/2 to 2 5/8. Several insiders at thecompany have been taking advantage of the stock's low priceto boost their holdings, this newspaper reported.   Profit-taking hit Georgia Gulf, which fell 3/4 to 9 7/8 inactive trading. The stock ran up nearly 30% at the end of theyear, partly because of a ratings upgrade by First Boston.   The American Stock Exchange Market Value Index fell 1.54to 306.57. Volume totaled 8,380,000 shares.</TEXT></DOC>